# Mobile Safe-Area Layout

Every React Native screen MUST account for device safe areas (status bar, notch, dynamic island, home gesture area). Failure to do so causes content to be hidden under the status bar or home indicator.

## Rules (MUST follow on every screen)

- ALWAYS import `useSafeAreaInsets` from `react-native-safe-area-context` in any screen-level component.
- ALWAYS apply `paddingTop: insets.top` (or `+ n` for extra breathing room) when the screen has no native navigation header (i.e., `headerShown: false` or standalone header components).
- ALWAYS apply `paddingBottom: insets.bottom` for fixed footer buttons / CTAs so they don't overlap the gesture bar.
- For screens that DO use a native React Navigation header (`headerShown: true`), the header already handles the top inset — do NOT add extra `paddingTop: insets.top` to the body content.
- Never hardcode `paddingTop: 0` on a screen container.
- Never rely only on Simulator/Emulator — test on real devices with notch or dynamic island.

## Example — screen without native header

```tsx
import { useSafeAreaInsets } from "react-native-safe-area-context";

export function MyScreen() {
  const insets = useSafeAreaInsets();

  return (
    <ScrollView
      contentContainerStyle={[
        styles.content,
        { paddingTop: insets.top + 12, paddingBottom: insets.bottom + 16 },
      ]}
    />
  );
}
```

## Example — screen WITH native header (headerShown: true)

```tsx
// No insets.top needed — the header already handles it
export function MyScreen() {
  const insets = useSafeAreaInsets();

  return (
    <View style={{ flex: 1 }}>
      <FlatList
        contentContainerStyle={{ paddingBottom: insets.bottom + 16 }}
        ...
      />
    </View>
  );
}
```
